@node distribution "Distribution"
   *** Distribution ***

   At this point this script is freely distributable.  It may be passed around by
pretty much any means available.  AS LONG AS:

   1.) You DON'T charge for it! I wrote it and if anyone is gonna make money off
       this than it should be me, you lazy bums. :)

   2.) The archive is distributed in its COMPLETE form. ie: the script file and
       the documantation will not be altered.

   This script will be posted to Aminet and possibly other sites and the may very
well be a support site for it soon after its initial posting to Aminet.  So for
those of you with Internet access there should be no excuse for not having an 
original copy of the archive.

   Heck. If I am lucky, Jeff Webster may even decide to put this in his distribution
of the ChatBox archive. (hint hint) :)

   Any questions, comments, or smartass remarks can be sent to me at:

   bobm@lcc.net

@endnode

@node overview "Overview"
   ***  Overview ***

   This is the non-GUI version of a little script I decided to write to enhance
the already great capabilities of the ChatBox IRC client.  One of the few minor
problems I found with ChatBox was its inability to save any nicks set for
Notify.  I for one have a number of friends on IRC and hate to have to type in
Notifys for them every time I log on IRC so therefore this script was finally born.

   Basically all this script does add a couple of commands to ChatBox and add to
and delete from a text file the nicks you want set for notify.

   Now, some people may ask, Why am I using ChatBox when there is a very popular
GUI IRC client available?  Well, there are a number of reasons.  First of all, 
I love the GUI interface of the Amiga operating system, Its beauty and its 
simplicity.  But, I also love the power and flexibility of the shell.  I find 
ChatBox to be a terrific compromise between the power and complexity of the
ircII shell IRC client and the GUI of "The Other", MUI driven, IRC client. 
Which brings me to my second reason.

   I really like MUI.  But, it is sometimes overused in an application or used for
applications that are better off without a GUI.  Decreasing there power for ease 
of use and a pretty interface.  Also, for some applications, MUI needs a relativly
fast system, which I for one do not have. :(  I still use my first system, A 
wonderful and still going strong A500.  I have expanded it a decent amount but
do to lack of resources ($$) I haven't been able to add an accelerator to it yet.
Heck, I would love to buy an A4000T but I am still waiting for that check for 
winning the lottery...okay...I am still waiting to WIN the lottery. :)  So my 
poor little systme has a little trouble running some MUI appllcations at a 
somewhat, by todays standards, sluggish 7Mhz. One of those applications is
"The Other" IRC client.  Not only is it a bit slow reacting but it causes all
the wonderful ARexx scripts I write for it react slow also.  

   That is why I switched to ChatBox.  It has the power and flexibility of a client
like ircII with its extended command set combined with the beauty and ease of use
of just the right amount of GUI.  And it doesn't use MUI.  It uses the 
ClassAct GUI library which is quite a bit faster and looks nice too.

   Well, I have rambled on quite enough I think.  I congradulate you if you have
waded through to this point even. :)  Now...On with the show.
 
@endnode

@node required "Requirements"
   *** Requirements ***

   * An Amiga :)
   
   * Must be running ARexx. (if you aren't, see your Amiga docs to find out how)

   * The ChatBox IRC client must be running.

   * Friends (or enemies) that you need to put on Notify. :)

   Thats pretty much it.
@endnode

@node setup "Installation and Setup"

   *** Installation and Setup ***

   The Installation and setup are pretty simple.

   1) copy Notiphy.cb to wherever you have your ChatBox rexx files.
      If you don't have anyplace yet than create the dir: rexx
      in your ChatBox dir and place Notiphy.cb there.

   2) copy the file: ircrc.not into your ChatBox dir.

   3) copy the docs wherever you feel like it.

   4) add the following to your alias file. (ircrc.als - see Chatbox.guide)
      or type it in every time you run ChatBox.

      /alias nON   exec rexx/Notiphy.cb L
      /alias na    exec rexx/Notiphy.cb ADD $0
      /alias nd    exec rexx/Notiphy.cb DEL $0
      /alias nv    exec rexx/Notiphy.cb V
      /alias nhelp exec rexx/Notiphy.cb HELP
                        ^^^^^
   NOTE: this----------/^^^^^ will possibly be different depending on where
         you have your rexx scripts for ChatBox located!

   6) Start Notiphy from ChatBox by using the command:  /nON
      (see the Command section for details)

   When Notiphy is started it will put all the nicks in the notify text file
   on Notify.

@endnode

@node commands "Commands"

   *** Commands ***

   /nON        - This starts Notiphy and loads the additional commands
                 needed for the program. Then it loads all the nicks
                 from the notify list.

   /na <nick>  - Adds a nick to the notify file and places that nick on
                 Notify on IRC.

   /nd <nick>  - Deletes a nick from the notify file and removes it from
                 Notify on IRC.

   /nHelp      - sends a brief help message to your ChatBox window.

   /nv         - sends a brief version message to your ChatBox window.

@endnode


    
